menu "breadboard: bb_mdns"

config BB_MDNS_AUTOREGISTER
    bool "Auto-init bb_mdns via bb_registry"
    default y
    help
        When enabled, bb_mdns self-initializes through bb_registry at
        bb_registry_init(server). Disable to skip the automatic init while
        keeping the component's public C API (caller must invoke bb_mdns_init manually).

config BB_MDNS_BROWSE_REFRESH_INTERVAL_S
    int "Periodic browse-refresh interval (seconds, 0 disables)"
    default 60
    range 0 3600
    help
        IDF's mDNS browser only fires the notify callback on PTR
        state changes (add / remove). Active advertisers re-announcing
        with the same TTL are silently refreshed in IDF's cache, so
        consumers never see a "still alive" event for stable peers and
        their last-seen timestamps stagnate.

        At this interval, bb_mdns deletes and re-creates each active
        browse subscription, forcing a fresh PTR scan. Any responder
        produces a fresh add notification; any peer that doesn't reply
        in the new query window fires its removal callback first.
        Set to 0 to disable the periodic refresh.

config BB_MDNS_EVT_POOL_SIZE
    int "Notifier event pool size"
    default 8
    range 4 64
    help
        Pre-allocated bb_mdns_evt_t slots used by the notifier callback to
        hand events to the dispatch task without per-event malloc. IDF's
        mDNS task delivers a linked list of mdns_result_t in one callback,
        so this caps how many peers can be queued in a single notify burst
        before events are dropped (logged as "event pool exhausted").

        Each slot is ~588 bytes; default 8 fits 1-8 peers and saves ~4.7 KB
        BSS vs the old default of 16. Raise to 16+ for large LANs.

config BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX
    int "mDNS coalescing batch size"
    default 16
    range 2 64
    help
        Maximum number of peer events buffered in the coalescing batch before
        a synchronous flush is triggered.  Two file-scope static arrays
        (s_batch and s_batch_item, each bb_mdns_evt_t[BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX]) are
        sized by this value, so each unit costs ~516 bytes of .bss per array
        (~1 KB total per step).  At the default of 16 the two arrays occupy
        ~8.2 KB of .bss combined.

        Lowering this on small-heap boards (e.g. ESP32-S2 with ~148 KB total
        heap) reclaims BSS at the cost of dropping peers beyond the batch
        within a single refresh burst — any dropped peers are recovered on the
        next periodic browse refresh (~60 s).  Setting it to 4 reclaims ~12.4 KB
        relative to the default of 16.

        Raise above 16 only on boards with ample RAM and networks with unusually
        large peer counts.

config BB_MDNS_TXT_PENDING_MAX
    int "Maximum pending TXT key/value pairs before mDNS starts"
    default 4
    range 1 16
    help
        bb_mdns_set_txt() may be called before the mDNS service has started.
        Pending writes are held in a static table of this size and flushed
        when the service starts. Default 4 covers typical usage (update,
        board, fw, custom key). Raise if more TXT keys are set pre-start.

endmenu
